WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.500
During the Korean War, also known as the 6.25 War, a large number of refugees gathered in Busan.

00:07.500 --> 00:13.500
As the population rapidly increased, there was no flat land left to build houses.

00:13.500 --> 00:17.300
As a result, many people moved up the hillsides.

00:17.300 --> 00:21.000
One of those hillsides was Ami-dong.

00:21.000 --> 00:24.500
This area had originally been a Japanese cemetery.

00:24.500 --> 00:28.300
After Korea’s liberation, the cemetery remained.

00:28.300 --> 00:34.300
For refugees, it became a practical place to build simple shelters from wind and rain.

00:34.300 --> 00:38.500
Building a house requires a strong foundation.

00:38.500 --> 00:42.700
However, at that time, construction materials were extremely scarce.

00:42.700 --> 00:49.700
As a result, large tombstones were often used as retaining walls or even as floors.

00:49.700 --> 00:57.500
Gravestones were also used as foundations, pillars, walls, and sometimes even as stair steps.

00:57.500 --> 01:03.500
At the entrance of the village, there is a well-known example called the “House on the Gravestone.”

01:03.500 --> 01:13.500
According to historical records, when human remains were discovered during construction,
they were treated with respect and sometimes moved to nearby temples.